df_cocktails <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-05-26/cocktails.csv')

df_boston <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-05-26/boston_cocktails.csv')
## Rows: 3643 Columns: 6
## -- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (4): name, category, ingredient, measure
## dbl (2): row_id, ingredient_number
## 
## i Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## i Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
## scrape top 50 cocktails from vinepair.com
df_top <- 
  read_html("https://vinepair.com/articles/50-most-popular-cocktails-world-2017/") %>% 
  html_node("body") %>% 
  xml_find_all("//h3") %>% 
  html_text() %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  separate(value, into = c("rank", "drink"), sep = "\\. ") %>% 
  filter(!is.na(drink)) %>% 
  mutate(
    rank = as.numeric(rank),
    drink = case_when(
      drink == "Corpse Reviver No. 1" ~ "Corpse Reviver", 
      drink == "Old Cuban" ~ "The Old Cuban",
      drink == "Ramos Gin Fizz" ~ "New Orleans Gin Fizz",
      drink == "Vieux Carr" ~ "Carre Reprise",
      TRUE ~ drink)
  )

## top cocktails with ingredients
df_cocktails_top <-
  df_boston %>% 
  dplyr::select(drink = name, ingredient, ingredient_number) %>% 
  mutate(
    drink = case_when(
      drink == "Blood and Sand" ~ "Blood & Sand", 
      drink == "Rum Old-Fashioned" ~ "Rum Old Fashioned",
      TRUE ~ drink
    ),
    data = "boston"
  ) %>% 
  full_join(
    df_cocktails %>%
      dplyr::select(drink, ingredient, ingredient_number) %>%
      mutate(
        drink = case_when(
          drink == "Spritz" ~ "Aperol Spritz",
          drink == "Dark and Stormy" ~ "Dark N Stormy",
          drink == "Pina Colada" ~ "Pia Colada",
          drink == "Tommy's Margarita" ~ "Tommys Margarita",
          TRUE ~ drink
        ),
        data = "cocktails"
      )
  ) %>%
  full_join(df_top) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(rank), !is.na(ingredient))
## Joining, by = c("drink", "ingredient", "ingredient_number", "data")
## Joining, by = "drink"
## similarity of recipes
df_cocktails_sim <-
  df_cocktails_top %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = ingredient_number,
    values_from = ingredient,
    names_prefix = "ingredient_no_"
  ) %>% 
  group_by(drink) %>% 
  arrange(desc(data)) %>% 
  slice(1) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  unite(
    "ingredients", 
    starts_with("ingredient_no_"),
    sep = " "
  ) %>% 
  mutate(ingredients = str_remove_all(ingredients, "NA\\s|\\sNA")) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, ingredients) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>%
  count(rank, word) %>% 
  pairwise_similarity(rank, word, n, upper = F, sort = T)

graph_tbl <- 
  df_cocktails_sim %>%
  as_tbl_graph() 
set.seed(12345) #202022
layout <- create_layout(graph_tbl, layout = 'igraph', algorithm = 'nicely')

net <-
  ggraph(layout) +
    geom_edge_link(
      color = "grey40",
      edge_width = .2,
      show.legend = FALSE
    ) +
    geom_node_point(
      aes(
        fill = -as.numeric(name),
        fill = after_scale(colorspace::lighten(fill, .3, space = "HLS")),
        color = after_scale(colorspace::darken(fill, .1, space = "HLS")), 
        size = -as.numeric(name)
      ),
      shape = 21,
      stroke = 1.5
    ) +
    geom_node_text(
      aes(
        color = as.numeric(name) > 29,
        label = as.numeric(name)
      ), 
      family = "Paytone One",
      fontface = "bold",
      size = 3.5,
      vjust = .5, 
      hjust = .5
    ) +
    scale_color_manual(
      values = c("#5834A5", "#E8DCAD"), ## colorspace::lighten(c("#4B2C8C", "#E6D8A4"), .1, space = "HLS")
      guide = F
    ) +
    rcartocolor::scale_fill_carto_c(
      palette = "ag_Sunset",
      guide = F
    ) +
    scale_size(
      range = c(8, 18),
      guide = F
    ) +
    labs(caption = "Visualization by Cdric Scherer    Annual List of the Worlds Best-Selling Classic Cocktails by Drinks International    Ingredient Data by Mr. Boston Bartender's Guide & Kaggle")

ranks <-
  df_top %>% 
  full_join(df_cocktails_top) %>% 
  count(drink, rank, data) %>% 
  mutate(rank_na = if_else(is.na(data), NA_real_, rank)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_text(
      aes(
        x = .95, y = rank,
        label = glue::glue("{rank}."),
        color = rank_na,
        color = after_scale(colorspace::lighten(color, .3, space = "HLS"))
      ),
      family = "Overpass Mono",
      fontface = "bold",
      size = 3.5,
      hjust = 1
    ) +
    geom_text(
      aes(
        x = 1, y = rank,
        label = drink,
        color = rank_na,
        color = after_scale(colorspace::lighten(color, .3, space = "HLS"))
      ),
      family = "Overpass",
      fontface = "bold",
      size = 3.5,
      hjust = 0
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 4)) +
    scale_y_reverse() +
    rcartocolor::scale_color_carto_c(
      palette = "ag_Sunset",
      na.value = "grey35",
      direction = -1,
      guide = F
    ) +
    theme_void()
## Joining, by = c("rank", "drink")
title <-
  ggplot(tibble(x = 1:10, y = 1:10)) +
    labs(
      title = "How Similar are the 50 Most Popular Cocktails in the World?",
      subtitle = 'Now that many bars are serving drinks again all around the world after lockdowns due to the COVID-19 pandemic, you might want to take this\nopportunity to finally taste the worlds best classic cocktails of 2020!\n\nThe "Annual List of the Worlds Best-Selling Classic Cocktails" is based on a survey by Drinks International. The trade publication for the\nalcoholic industry surveyed the best bars around the globe, asking them to rank the 10 best-selling classic cocktails at their establishments.\nThe network below shows the similarity of ingredients of 41 cocktails from this list that were also contained in the two data sets from Kaggle.\nIn case you want to try a popular but unusual drink with regards to the recipe: Go order an "Amaretto Sour", a "Paloma" or an "Aperol Spritz"\nas the cocktail of your choice next time you are visiting a bar together with your partner or friends!'
    )

ggdraw(net) +
  draw_plot(ranks, .84, .985, .2, .7, hjust = 0, vjust = 1) +
  draw_plot(title, .03, .985, 0, .7, hjust = 0, vjust = 1)
